# Registration Form

Your registration form is how new members join your organization. A clear, well-organized form makes the signup process smooth and welcoming. This page walks you through each setting and shares a few tips along the way.

> You can preview your form anytime: [open registration form](<%= new_members_member_url(subdomain: Current.org.members_subdomain) %>). It's worth testing it on mobile too, since many people will sign up from their phone.

## Introduction Text {#introduction}

The subtitle appears just below the form title. A sentence or two is ideal here: a short welcome, or a link to your website for more details.

The [subtitle setting](/settings#registration) supports rich text, but keep in mind that people who reach your form are already interested. They need a clear path to sign up, not a full presentation of your organization.

**Good example:**

*Welcome! Find all details about our CSA on [our website](https://example.com). Fill out this form to join us.*

**Better to avoid:**

*Our CSA was founded in 2012 and delivers organic vegetables from our farm in the countryside. We work with 3 partner farms and offer baskets in 12 different sizes. Pricing is based on a solidarity model where...* (and 200 more words)

## Text Styling Tips {#text-styling}

All rich text fields in the [registration settings](/settings#registration) use the text editor. Here are a few things worth knowing about how your formatting shows up in the form:

- **Explanation text appears smaller** than the form fields themselves. This is intentional: it creates a visual hierarchy where the choices stand out and the explanations stay in the background. Heavy formatting (lots of bold, lots of headings) works against this.
- **Headings** render as subtle sub-headings, not large titles. They add a bit of structure without dominating the page. In most cases, bold text works just as well.
- **Bold text** is great for highlighting key info like prices or deadlines, but loses its effect if you bold entire sentences or paragraphs.
- **Short paragraphs work best.** Two or three sentences is plenty. People tend to scan rather than read every word.
- **Link to your website** for longer explanations rather than putting everything in the form.

You'll notice a word count indicator in the settings editor when text gets long. It's just a gentle nudge, not a hard limit. If you're over the threshold, it might be worth trimming or moving some content to your website.

## Basket Sizes {#basket-sizes}

[Basket sizes](/basket_sizes) are the core of your registration form. Each visible basket size appears as a choice for new members.

- **Name**: What members see (e.g., "Small", "Family"). A self-explanatory name helps: "Small (1–2 people)" is clearer than just "Small".
- **Description**: Overrides the auto-generated text (price × deliveries). Useful when the default doesn't quite capture what you need.
- **Visibility**: Set a basket size to invisible if it's only for admins (e.g., a special rate). Invisible sizes won't appear in the form.
- **Display order**: Controlled by the [order mode setting](/settings#registration), either by name, by price, or by custom priority.

## Basket Complements {#basket-complements}

[Basket complements](/basket_complements) (bread, cheese, eggs, etc.) appear after the basket size selection.

- **Checkbox vs. quantity mode**: The [complement quantities setting](/settings#registration) controls whether members see simple checkboxes (subscribe or not) or quantity fields (0, 1, 2...).
- **Complement text**: An optional introduction before the list. One sentence is usually enough to explain what's available.
- **Display order**: Controlled by the [order mode setting](/settings#registration).

