## Depots {#depots}

[Depots](/depots) are the pickup locations members choose from. The depot address is always displayed alongside the name, with a map link so members can check the location.

- **Name**: What members see. Keep it short and recognizable (e.g., a neighborhood name or a well-known landmark).
- **Description**: Optional text shown below the depot name. Useful for pickup hours or specific instructions.
- **Visibility**: Hide depots that are full or admin-only.
- **Display order**: Controlled by the [order mode setting](/settings#registration).

### Depot Groups {#depot-groups}

If your organization has many depots (8 or more), [depot groups](/depot_groups) make a big difference. They organize depots into logical sections so members can quickly find their area.

- **Example groups**: "Pickup at farm", "City relay points", "Home delivery"
- **Information text**: Optional text shown above each group's depots. A good place for shared info like pickup hours or general instructions. One sentence is usually enough.
- **Order priority**: Controls which group appears first.

Without groups, a flat list of 15+ depots can feel overwhelming. Groups help members zero in on their area and then pick a specific location.

## Delivery Cycles {#delivery-cycles}

If you use multiple [delivery cycles](/delivery_cycles) (weekly, bi-weekly, seasonal), members choose one during registration. See the [delivery cycles handbook page](/handbook/deliveries#delivery-cycles) for detailed configuration.

- **Custom label**: Override the default "Deliveries" heading with the [delivery cycle label setting](/settings#registration).
- **Display order**: Controlled by the [order mode setting](/settings#registration).
- **Depot association**: Cycles can be linked to specific depots. The form then automatically filters available cycles based on the selected depot.

If a cycle is only relevant to certain depots, setting up the depot-cycle associations means members will only see valid choices.

## Additional Explanation Text {#extra-text}

Two settings control the explanation text in the membership section:

- **[Extra text](/settings#registration)**: Appended after the auto-generated text (fiscal year, trial baskets, annual fee, shares).
- **[Extra text only](/settings#registration)**: Replaces the auto-generated text entirely. Only useful if the default text really doesn't fit your needs.

The auto-generated text already covers the essentials, so the extra text is best used for what's specific to your organization. If you find yourself writing more than a short paragraph, consider linking to your website instead.

## More Info Fields {#more-info}

Two optional fields can be shown on the form:

- **Profession**: Hidden by default. Enable it in [settings](/settings#registration) if it's useful to your organization.
- **"How did you hear about us?"** ("Come from"): Helpful for understanding how people find you. It's a low-effort question for members and gives you interesting data over time.

Both fields can be set to hidden, visible, or required.

## Legal Documents {#documents}

You can require members to acknowledge up to four types of documents:

- Charter
- Statutes
- Terms of Service
- Privacy Policy

For each, provide a URL pointing to the document on your website. When a URL is set, members must check a confirmation box before submitting the form.

## Display Order Settings {#order-settings}

Several elements in the form can be reordered:

| Element | Setting | Options |
|---------|---------|---------|
| Basket sizes | [Order mode](/settings#registration) | Name, price (asc/desc), priority |
| Basket complements | [Order mode](/settings#registration) | Name, price (asc/desc), priority |
| Depots | [Order mode](/settings#registration) | Name, price (asc/desc), priority |
| Delivery cycles | [Order mode](/settings#registration) | Name, priority |

When using "priority" mode, set the "Order priority" field on each item. Lower values appear first.

## A Few Tips {#tips}

1. **Keep the form focused.** Every extra paragraph makes the form feel longer. Your website is the place for storytelling; the form is for action.
2. **Test on mobile.** Tap through the entire flow on a phone at least once.
3. **Use depot groups** if you have more than 8 depots.
4. **Limit solidarity pricing options** to around 4–6 choices.
5. **Preview after changes.** After updating settings, check how the form looks: [open registration form](<%= new_members_member_url(subdomain: Current.org.members_subdomain) %>).
6. **Short text, clear labels.** If a member needs to read a full paragraph to understand a choice, the label could probably be improved.
